medical_history.chief_complaint: Patient presented for routine 22 weeks’ gestation visit.
medical_history.history_of_present_illness: Patient's previous pregnancies ended with normal vaginal delivery and an abortion. During current pregnancy, antenatal abdominal ultrasonography findings reported as normal. A cystic mass was observed on vaginal examination and pelvic ultrasonography. Laparotomy was conducted with no ovarian cyst found, and postoperative MR imaging revealed an anterior sacral meningocele (ASM). At 38 weeks’ gestation, elective cesarean section was performed, with repeated MR imaging showing no increase in meningocele size at 35 weeks.
medical_history.past_medical_history: Patient had been pregnant three times, given birth once, and had one abortion. No other relevant medical history specified.
medical_history.family_history: Family history indicated that the patient’s mother died of unexplained fever. The patient's asymptomatic 5-year-old daughter (from second pregnancy) underwent radiography that revealed a scimitar-shaped sacrum and MR imaging indicated anterior sacral meningocele.
